<DOC><DOCNO> AP891210-0053 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-12-10-89 1819EST</FILEID><FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     12-10 0359</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0370</SECOND><HEAD>Snow and Freezing Winds Blamed for Highway Deaths</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Snow in the northern Plains and ice storms in North Carolina andGeorgia, blamed for at least nine deaths over the weekend,threatened other states Sunday in the path of storms and chillingwinds.   Heavy snow hampered traffic and caused delays at Denver'sStapleton International Airport on Sunday, and caused a dozen-carpileup on Interstate 25 near Johnstown that blocked traffic for twohours. A motorist's death in Colorado Springs was blamed on thestorm.   In addition to Colorado, snow showers fell over western New Yorkstate, much of Ohio, Upper Michigan, northern Lower Michigan, Iowa,southern Minnesota, the Dakotas, eastern Nebraska and the NebraskaPanhandle, western Kansas, New Mexico and Montana.   In North Carolina, the first wintry storm of the season wasresponsible for three deaths Friday and four Saturday, authoritiessaid. The storm also knocked out power to thousands of householdsand toppled two television towers before moving out to sea Sunday.   ``This is one of the most severe storms we have had,'' saidNorth Carolina Power spokesman Randy Shillingburg. ``In some areas... in Roanoke Rapids there are probably three, possibly fourinches of ice.''   The northeast Georgia mountains were blanketed with 3 to 4inches of snow Saturday, but on Sunday temperatures rose into the40s under sunny skies.   A motorist's death in Georgia on Saturday was blamed on road ice.   Snowfall overnight measured 11 inches at Winner, S.D., 6 inchesat Pickstown, S.D., 3 to 6 inches over northwest Iowa, 5 inches atNewcastle, Neb., and Yankton, S.D., 4 inches at Laurel andBloomfield, Neb., and 3 inches at Rapid City S.D., and over upperMichigan.   Four inches of snow fell on Denver during the morning, 2 inchesfell at Colorado Springs and Limon, Colo., and one inch fell atBillings and Great Falls, Mont., and Pueblo, Colo.   The low temperature for the Lower 48 states was 21 degrees belowzero at Houlton, Maine.   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EST ranged from 2degrees below zero at Cutbank, Mont., to 82 degrees at San Angelo,Texas.</TEXT></DOC>